{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_melville_ver02/data/sn84026749/00222254036/1923101501/0634.xml":{"full_text":"4\n1 AUTOMOBILES\nREPORTED\nSTOLEN\nThieves Get Loot Valued at\n$5,000 As Result of One\nDay\u2019.s Activities.\nSeven automobiles, worth $5,000,\nwere stolen from the streets yester\nday and last night, according to\npolice reports.\nDr. J. R. Sharp, 1861 Wyoming\navenue northwest, reported that a\nHudson touring car was stolen from\nin front of his home about midnight\nlast night. Thojnas M. Steadman,\n3402 Georgia avenue northwest,\ncomplained of the theft of his Oak\nland roadster, equipped with a\nWinter top, bet.vten midnight and 6\no\u2019clock this morning.\nAlden Sehey, 446 R street north\nwest, reported h automobile stolen\nfrom Thirteenth and T streets\nnorthwest about 2 o\u2019clock this morn\ning. It was a five-passenger Buick.\nHarry S. Aubinee, 701 Webster\nstreet northwest, lost a Studebaker\nroadster with a red body from in\nfront of his home.\nOthers who reported cafs stolen\nare: Charles Clark, 1619 Seven\nteenth street northwest; Mabel E.\nNordhal, 1424 Shepherd street north\nwest, and Joseph Ippolito, 81 K\nstreet northwest. Miss Nordhal lost\nFord coupe and the other two re-\nP\u00b0 rt ed Ford touring cars stolen.\nms mot\nima\u00dfklT\nSpend 5c Save 5c\nfISL I SB\nj./Ib ,a OUKCII uOAF\nTuesday Wednesday Values\nMillbrook Eggstw -39 c\nCarefully Selected\nCreamery\u00dfutter 7 a t\u00ab f io\u00b0e m *bsOc\nFine Quality\nSirloin Steak, lb. 35c\nGenuine Native Beef\nSmithfield Shoulders ib. 21c\nFried or Baked\u2014A King\u2019s Dish\nStew Beef, lb. 10c\nLarge Lux, pkg. 25c\nMuch cheaper than the small package\nBeechnut Spaghetti 111 c\nWith tomato sauce and cheese\nCream of Wheat, pkg. 19c\nCorn, Q o u r ee o n n A T n o n p e 3 Cans 25c\nTomatoes, No. 3 Can L 23c\nMinaret Dates, pkg. 15c\nDromedary Dates, pkg. 22c\n1923 Crop-Paper Shelled\nAlmonds, lb29c\nKeystone Flour,\n5 lbs. 21c, 12 lbs. 43c, 24 lbs. 83c\nAn absolute guarantee of satisfaction\nCider, gal3sc\nEvaporated Milk lOVc\nCarnation, Van Camp, Borden or Pet\nCampbell\u2019sTomatoSoup 8c\nSugar, 10 lbs. 98c\n1 _ i\nOpera Singer Scotti\nBack From Italy\nFlat Broke\nNEW YORK, Oct. 15.\u2014An\ntonio Scotti, the famous bari\ntone of the Meropolitan Opera\nHouse, who will celebrate thia\nseason as his twenty-fifth year\nas a metnber of the Metropoli\ntan organization, arrived on the\nsteamship Conte Verde from\nNaples.\nThe baritone said he was\nbroke. \u201cI am a poor man,\u201d he\ndeclared. \u201cTwo years of opera\nventure took my money. Yet,\nI should worry. I came into\nthis world with nothing, so why\nshould I worry about taking\nany away.\u201d\nScotti has been in Italy five\nmonths. He says it is not the\nItaly of old, but a revivified\nItaly, an Italy of youth and\nvitality.\nPOLICE FACE JAR BARRAGE,\nTHEN GET 30 GALLONS\nJars of Ikldbr are unwleldly\nmissiles, as members of Jbe ce\nsquad are ready to testify today,\nfollowing a raid on the, premises at\n1245 South Capitol street Mst night.\nThe squad says it was made im\nprovised targets for a barrage of\ncorn liquor Jars.\nLieut. O. T. Davis. Sergeant Mc-\nQuade, Patrolman Fink, and \u2018\u2018Lone\nWolf\u201d Asher staged the raid. Wil\nliam Bradley, colored and his wife,\nEmma, were rrrested on charges\nof selling and possession of liquor.\nThe police say they found thirty\ngallons of alleged wine and corn\nliquor in the place.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES The National Daily MONDAY, OCTOBER 15, 1923.\nBIMLN CH 1\nIS MH OF i\n\nCapitol Heights Bovine, Said to\nHave Died in Tremens, Re- s\nsponsible for Tip.\nThe thirsty folk of Capitol J\nHeights, Md., noir-neighbor of the 5\nDistrict, had their suppl.es dealt a\n.death blow yesterday when two\nrevenue agents, Linton S. Evans\nand J. H. Estes, raided five places,\narrested three persons, found one\n200-gallon still, one fifty-gallon still,\na large quantity of mash, thirty\ngallons of corn liquor, and a barrel\nof w.ne.\nThe three men arrested and the\ncharges against them are Frame\nHuber, manufacturing; Philip\ning, and George Proctor, manufac\nturing and illegal possession. They\nwill be taken to Baltimore for ar\nraignment \u00bboday.\nOne of the stories emanating from\nthe Heights is that the agents re\nceived their first tip that liquor\nwas being manufactured there when\na cow staggered about town, plainly\nunder the Influence of Bacchnalian\nspirits. It is said that the cow de\nveloped a thirst for liquor and lost\nall liking for aqua purs. Under the\nstigma of having a drunken cow in\ntown, the Capitol Heights residents\ngrew Indignant.and the agents were\ntipped off. The cow died an un\ntimely death last week from what\nwas declared to have been delirium\ntremens.\nAccording to George Finger,\nmayor of the town, bootlegging has\nbeen prevalent there for some time.\nCases of drunkenness are not infre\nquent and numerous complaints\nhave been made to the prohibition\nunit for better enforcement of the\nVolstead law. Mayor Finger ex\npressed the hope that the raids\n-would mop up the wet spots in the\ntown.\nsenitor'suck\nof mtosE\nPUNS HILL\nMaryland Congressman Says\nHe Got Idea for Fruit Juice\nTest From Virginia.\nIn somewhat sarcastic vein, Con\ngressman John Philip Hill of Mary\nland, whose (famous \u201cfruit juice\u201d ex\nperiments on his estate earned him\na\u2018. vocal lambasting at Saturday\u2019s\nsessions of the citizens\nconference, last night retfrHed to his\ncastigator, Senator Carter Glass of\nVirginia.\nHe expressed himself \u201csurprised\u201d\nthat Mr. Glass permitted himself to\nexhibit the very grave ignorance of\nlaw and facts that led him to refer\nto me as he did.\u201d The solon was\nquoted as declaring that \u201cif Mr. Hill\nwere a Virginian and had attempted\nhis wine-making experiment there,\nhe would have been jailed.\u201d\n\"Does he not know,\u201d Inquires Con\ngressman Hill, \u201cthat no State officer\nhas anything to do with putting\npeople Into jail under Federal laws\nin Maryland? I am doubly pained\nat Senator Glass\u2019 speech without\nknowledge; first, because one of my\ngreat-great-great grandfathers was\nattorney general of Virginia long be\nfore Senator Glass entered the news\npaper business; second, the idea of\nmy fruit-juice test, for which the\nSenator wishes to jail me without\ntrial, came from Virginia.\u201d\nORimFE,\nDECLARES\nBRIAN\nOpponents Have No Chance to\nOverthrow It in Congress,\n\u201cCommoner\u201d Declares.\nDeclaring that talk of modifying\nthe prohibition law to legalize beer\nand light wines is a \u201cfratld,\u201d Wil-\nI liam Jennings Bryan, speaking in\ni Calvary Baptist Church last night,\nI announced he would object to dry\ni agents\u2019 drinking \u201con the ground that\nI it is unconstitutional.\u201d\ni \"Tn the future,\u201d he said, \u201cno man\nshould have charge of the enforce\nment of the law who himself drinks!\nintoxicating liquor.\u201d\ni As to the movement for modifica\ni tion, Bryan said that the most the\ni \u201cwets\u201d could hope for is to get a ma\ni jority of one vote in the House to\nI prevent appropriations for dry en\nforcement.\n\u201cWe have elected five successive\ndry Congresses.\u201d ho told his audi\nence. \u2018The talk of bringing back\ni light wines and beer is a fraud, and\nI no one knows it better than those\nI who speak of it. We have two-thirds\n;of the Senate. Then how can they\ni pass a bill modifying the Volstead\nI law?*\u2019\nHe advocated co-operation of State\nFederal, county and city authorities\nI n punishing violations of ih- law.\nMost of the great liquor warehouse\nI robberies, he said, were fakes.\nPAYNE TO DISCUSS\nRELATIONS WITH MEXICO\n\u2022John Barton Payne, chairman of\nI the American National Red Cross,\nw'.ll speak tomorrow night on\n\u201cI nit< <1 States-Mexlco Relations\u2019\u2019\nat the meeting of the International\nI Association of Art and Letters to\nbe held at the organization\u2019s club\n-house, 17J5 i street northwest, at\n8:30 o\u2019clock.\nMr i\u2019ayne represented the Unit, d\nStates in negotiations that resulted\n\u25a0in the recognition of Mexico\nD. c. guard exams for\nWEST POINT ON NOV. 15\nMajor C. Fred Cook, acting ad\njutant general of the District Na\ntional Guard, today announced that\nexaminations for entrance to the\nUnited States Military Academy at*\nWest Point for enlisted men in the\nDistrict National Guard would be\nheld about November 15.\nPOLICE BOOTLEGGERS HAVE\nTOO HIGH PRICES, CLAIM\nCHICAGO, Oct. 15. \u2014Chicago Sa\nloonkeepers revealed todav to the\nState\u2019s Attorney\u2019s office that they\nhave a real grievance. Uniformed\n$7,789 Worth of High-Grade\nWilton Rugs to Sell at $5,193\nA Sale In Which You Cannot Fail To Save!\nA change in manufacturing condi-\nii n \u201er\u00bb,,-a\u00dfgsr hiirarTaas=.\u2018\u2018-i. tions finds us with thousands of dol-\nl ars more rugs than we anticipated.\nJlV*j Hundreds of fine rugs in excess of our\nO Ira show room and storage capacity. To\nIn effect a reduction of stocks we have se-\n83 fine Wilton Rugs, products\nof\u00ae 'f W I s country\u2019s leading makers, and\nE S reduced them one-third in price. All\nfIL a e perfect quality, beautiful in design\nL and coloring, but rugs we cannot\nmatch or continue to obtain. Beyond\nifef doubt a wondrous opportunity, and\ntimely\u2014for right now you can use a\n'J* rW new rug to best advantage in your\nhome. By no means should you let this\nopportunity pass you by. Come to\nmorrow.\n20 Room Size M 2 Rugs\nReduced\n(ii) Wiltons, Formerly QQA ft A\np v t t $120.00. Reduced to tpOVgUv\nnu 111 ii. (2) Fine Wiltons. Formerly ft ft\n$139.50. Reduced t 0..... eptzO\u00abVV\nAttractive China forYour Home gs.<\u00bb wII H\u201eJ' e l) $70.00\nAt Prices Equally Attractive (3) Fine wflton& Formerly\nThis is the season for adding to the home supplies, particularly china. And co- $69.50. Reduced to\nf incident with your needs we bring about values like the